licensed EMS practitioners.
Proposed law adds a requirement for the commission to include in the recommended
requirements and standards of practice the authority for certain licensed EMS practitioners
to administer patient-carried, time-critical prescription medication to patients with rare
diseases, chronic illnesses, and special medical needs.
Proposed law authorizes EMS practitioners to administer the medication at the request of the
patient or patient's family and in accordance with protocols established by the EMS
practitioner's EMS medical director.
Proposed law provides that an EMS practitioner acting in accordance with the provisions of
proposed law shall be immune from civil liability, criminal prosecution, or disciplinary or
other adverse action under any professional licensing statute for any outcomes resulting from
the administration of the medication, unless personal injury results from the gross negligence
or willful or wanton misconduct of the EMS practitioner administering the medication.
Proposed law provides that proposed law shall be named and may be known as "The Danny's
Dose EMS Treatment Act".
Effective August 1, 2026.
(Amends R.S. 40:1133.4(A)(2); adds R.S. 40:1133.19)
Summary of Amendments Adopted by Senate
Senate Floor Amendments to engrossed bill
1. Moves the responsibility for establishing protocols for the administration of
patient-carried, time-critical prescription medication from the La. Emergency
Medical Services Commission to the EMS practitioner's EMS medical
director.
2. Requires the commission to include the authority for EMS practitioners to
administer the medications to certain patients in the requirements and
standards of practice submitted to the bureau.
